The Oasis-Pyramid Corridor is the logistical arc connecting desert roads, cistern law, and oasis administration to the three pyramids.
The oases were not passive waystations but the administrative infrastructure that made monumental construction, cosmic containment, and dynastic theology possible.
The Deepwell Confluence is a single deep limestone aquifer. Three fracture networks produce three oases at different volumes and mineral loads; the same aquifer connects through deep geological channels to cistern systems the pyramids depended on.
Keeper-of-Measure engineers built the first integrated infrastructure: road surveys calibrated by obelisk shadows, charter stones marking toll rates and distance, cistern waystations at regular intervals, and Waystone Circles at each oasis marking bearings to every major route.
The entire desert administration was an anti-amnesia system: the Black Sun Shard's memory-erosion effects reached the desert's fringes, and water-debt records had to be carved in stone because people forgot verbal agreements.
The three pyramids represent three different responses to the Shard: the Great Pyramid contains it through institutional precision, the Northern Pyramid guards the container with military force, the Southern Pyramid descends toward the source to understand it.
Three crises destroyed the unified corridor: the Ninth Meridian Rite's failure intensified drought, the Compact Crisis broke inter-oasis solidarity, and the Jackal Tribunal's fragmentation scattered the Solar Court's judicial apparatus across the desert.
Northern Oasis role: intake, verification, ration accounting — the first point of civil order caravans encounter after crossing the Eastern Desert. Water becomes policy here.
Southern Oasis role: convoy hardening, expedition marshalling, casualty and relic processing — the last point of civil order before the Southern Pyramid frontier. Policy becomes survival here.
External claimants: Midgaard catalogs and funds salvage, Kowloon preserves Keeper-era legal methodology, Kiess maintains commercial intelligence through Temple of Concord and Trade Syndics.
Active factional tensions include water-law administrators at three oases with divergent institutional priorities, relic commerce networks requiring oasis authentication, and Jackal Synod cult offshoots at every oasis and waystation.
The corridor is not a road between monuments; it is the civilization itself, of which the monuments are the most visible but not the most important components.

